        "meta_description": "HODINKEE Great Outdoors Week looks at the method for finding true north using the hands of an analog watch, and at compass watches from Seiko and Richard Mille",
        "meta_lang": "en",
        "meta_favicon": "/favicon.png",
        "meta_site_name": "Hodinkee",
        "canonical_link": "https://www.hodinkee.com/articles/the-last-article-youll-ever-need-on-finding-true-north-with-your-watch",
        "text": "This may be Great Outdoors Week on HODINKEE, but for some of us soft-handed, knowledge-worker, keyboard-tapping urbanites, the Great Outdoors may be something to be feared, as the first members of genus Homo, eons ago, looked out with fear upon the darkness of the night, listening to the distant growls of big cats looking for some tasty, tasty Australopithecus on which to sup. Peel away the thin veneer of civilization, and that terror-stricken primate isn't too far below the surface, especially if you find yourself straying off a trail and realizing, too late, that you don't know where you are and worse, don't know how to find your way back.\n\nOne of the most basic realities of getting un-lost, if you are lost, is making sure that you don't end up going around in circles and if you do have a general idea of the direction you ought to be traveling in order to emerge unscathed from the forest primeval, the first step is determining the cardinal directions – North, South, East, and West – so you can travel in the right direction.\n\nThe basic tool for orienting yourself in the wilderness is a compass – the mariner's friend as well, especially if you're dead reckoning (determining approximate position by taking a direction bearing and keeping track of speed, the same basic process used for dead reckoning in air navigation). Compasses can be thrown out of whack in a number of ways – I read once of an incident where a racing yacht found itself close to 30º off-course because a well-meaning crewman had gone over the boat, tightening every screw he could find, including the calibration screw for the compass.\n\nHaving a compass implies, of course, that you knew ahead of time that you'd need to navigate in the absence of a marked trail. Getting lost, however, is by definition not something you do on purpose. Being able to determine true North without a compass could mean the difference between making it back to the trail a little late, with a campfire story to laugh over, and spending an uncomfortable night in the open, or worse.\n\nThere are a number of ways to determine true North without a compass, and while they are all approximate, they are certainly much better than nothing. One of the oldest tricks in the book, at least in the Northern Hemisphere, is to look at where the moss is growing on tree trunks. The conventional wisdom is that you'll find the most moss on the north side, where there's less direct sunlight and there is more of the cool and damp that mosses favor. I heard this trick during my short and largely unsuccessful tenure as a Boy Scout but I've never found it to be true with any consistency.\n\nIf you have an analog watch with you, there is another and somewhat more reliable method, at least if it's daytime and the Sun is visible above the horizon. Lay the watch flat, and rotate it until the hour hand is lined up with the Sun, along a straight line of sight. The hour hand will form an angle with the number 12 on the dial. Divide the angle in half, and you'll have a line bisecting the dial – the end between the hour and and 12:00 is pointing South, and the other end is pointing North. Before noon, you measure clockwise from the hour hand, and after noon, counterclockwise. Remember, if your watch is set to Daylight Saving Time, you'll need to adjust the method accordingly (you can either set the hour hand back one hour, or just use the 1:00 mark instead of the 12:00 mark).\n\nThe principle is the same if you're in the Southern Hemisphere, but slightly different. If you're south of the Equator, the Sun is in the northern part of the sky. You hold your watch horizontally, and align the 12:00 marker with the Sun. North, not South, will be at the halfway point between the hour hand and the 12:00 mark.\n\nThis method works in the Northern Hemisphere specifically, and the reason is that the Sun, in the Northern Hemisphere, follows an arc across the Southern part of the sky (traditionally, artists have favored studios with Northern exposure, in order to get more diffuse, less harsh indirect light than you'd get from a Southern exposure). If you're in the Northern Hemisphere and facing the Sun directly at noon, you are looking more or less directly South, and using the position of the hour hand gives you the necessary hourly offset from which to determine where the Sun would be if it were noon instead of (say) 3PM.\n\nThe second point is that if it's nighttime, this method won't work. In the Northern Hemisphere, however, you only need to find Polaris, the North Star, which you can do by drawing an imaginary line from the two outermost stars of the bowl of the Big Dipper, until you hit the last star in the \"handle\" of the Little Dipper.\n\nWhile using a watch as a compass will only give you an approximate bearing, any sort of orientation is an improvement. Certainly it beats feeling your way through the trackless underbrush, singing, \"Lions and tigers and bears, oh my!\" under your breath."
